INFO.INTRO:
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;We&#039;ve
 created this glossary of our frequently used words and phrases. This is
 how we use these terms in this academy. If something is missing, or you don&#039;t understand the word or its description, please contact us!&amp;nbsp;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

ENTRY.DEFINITION:
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Abstraction of real-world phenomena. A feature may occur as a type or an instance. 
Feature type or feature instance shall be used when only one is meant.
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;[Source: ISO/TS 19101-1:2014, 4.1.11]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;Environmental Data Retrieval (EDR) API provides a family of lightweight 
interfaces to access Environmental Data resources. Each resource 
addressed by an EDR API maps to a defined query pattern.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;[Source: https://ogcapi.ogc.org/edr/]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align:left;&quot;&gt;A Service is a set of interfaces provided by an entity. The service provides functionality that distinguishes the entity from other entities.
In this context, an entity is a server on the web,
that provides a service, in most cases via HTTP.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align:left;&quot;&gt;[Source: ISO 19119:2005, Geographic information – Services,    &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.iso.org/iso/catalogue_detail.htm?csnumber=39890&quot;&gt;http://www.iso.org/iso/catalogue_detail.htm?csnumber=39890&lt;/a&gt;]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;An interface specifies a set of calls to an object (i.e. server) to execute a process
(e.g., transformation or query). Usually, it defines the name of the operations,
the list of parameters and allowed values.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;[Source: http://opengeospatial.github.io/e-learning/fundamental-concepts/text/networking.html#interface]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;A Web Map Tile Service (WMTS) is a standard by OGC that defines a set of interfaces for making web-based requests of map tiles 
of spatially referenced data using tile images with predefined content, 
extent, and resolution.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;WMTS is a predecessor for the newer OGC API - Tiles.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;auto&quot;&gt;A Record makes a resource discoverable by providing summary information about the resource. So, it is the atomic unit of information in a catalogue, providing a description (i.e. metadata) about a resource that the provider of the resource wishes to make discoverable.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p dir=&quot;auto&quot;&gt;The record building block defines the core schema of a 
catalogue record.  It includes a small number of properties that are 
common across all resource types.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p dir=&quot;auto&quot;&gt;[Source: https://github.com/opengeospatial/ogcapi-records &amp;amp; http://docs.ogc.org/DRAFTS/20-004.html]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;In this context, resources are things that would be useful to a user or 
developer, such as features, coverages, tiles/maps, assets, machine 
models, services, widgets, etc.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;[Source: http://docs.ogc.org/DRAFTS/20-004.html]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align:left;&quot;&gt;The FAIR principles aim to improve the &lt;strong&gt;F&lt;/strong&gt;indability, &lt;strong&gt;A&lt;/strong&gt;ccessibility, &lt;strong&gt;I&lt;/strong&gt;nteroperability and &lt;strong&gt;R&lt;/strong&gt;eusability
 (FAIR) of digital assets and, therefore, can act as general guiding 
principles to ensure the production and maintenance of good data and metadata.&amp;nbsp;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align:left;&quot;&gt;A draft standard is a document that has been proposed as a standard but 
has not yet been officially adopted or approved by the relevant 
standards organization.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align:left;&quot;&gt;A data model is a representation of data and the rules and relationships 
that govern it. It describes the data&#039;s structure, constraints, and semantics, and can be used to design and implement databases, 
information systems, and other data-intensive systems.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;&gt;Service that makes it possible to search for spatial data sets and services on the basis of the content of the corresponding metadata and to display the content of the metadata.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;&gt; [INSPIRE Directive, Art. 11].&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

